                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Last updated November 19, 2003 
<br />

<br />
Characters and Classes 
<br />

<br />
- 16 races and 48 classes. (Human, Erudite, High Elf, Wood Elf, Dark Elf, Half Elf, Barbarian, Troll, Ogre, Gnome, Halfling, Dwarf, Iksar, Kerran, Froglok, Ratonga) 
<br />

<br />
- Character creation is more streamlined than before. Taking a cue from “Asheron’s Call 2, you simply click on a statue representing the race you wish to be. Using a series of slider bars, you deform and tint the facial characteristics of your avatar. 
<br />

<br />
- Unparalleled character customization capabilities. In addition to the thousands of armor, weapons and items users will be able to equip, players will be able to customize their sex, race, height, weight, musculature, age, hair style and color, facial hair style and color, skin color, eye, nose, ear and chin shape and size, and the ability to add scars, freckles, tattoos where you wish (Allakhazam's) 
<br />

<br />
- Character stats are hidden, to avoid overwhelming new players. Experienced players can still open them up. 
<br />

<br />
Updated- Level 3 is when you first experience the new class system. That’s when you’ll finally select a profession from one of the Archetypes: Fighter, Rogue, Mage, Priest, or Tradesman (note: Druid was also listed as an archetype class in Computer Gaming World. We are still unsure if this was a printing error or true). 
<br />

<br />
- EQ2 dedicated tradesperson is a full-blown, experience-earning character in a non-confrontational environment. 
<br />

<br />
Updated - After picking an archetype at level 3, players will then choose a “Sub-class” at level 10. Then at level 20 they can choose a full “Class”. (So to become a paladin, the progression would be: Fighter at level 3, then Crusader at level 10, and finally Paladin at level 20. Also to be a Monk or something different you would choose: Fighter, then Brawler, and then Monk… etc etc). 
<br />

<br />
Updated - Characters can be developed up to level 50 at release (future expansions will offer higher levels) (EQ Stratics). 
<br />

<br />
- Combat classes will lack tradeskill abilities, and tradeskill classes will only have modest combat abilities. (E3) 
<br />

<br />
- Ratongas (half man, half rat) will be a new playable race. 
<br />

<br />
- The thing about racial modifiers right now is in terms of upper limits. An ogre and a gnome may bolth become fighters with roughly the same stats, but the Ogre will have a higher upper limit on his strength score, so he'll eventualy dish out more punishment then the Gnome, whose higher dexterity aptitude will turn him into a more nimble combatant. (Computer Gaming World, May 2003) 
<br />

<br />
- Characters will choose their classes, then choose the abilities and skills within those classes that they wish to concentrate on. All class abilities and skills will be available, but it will be up to the player to decide where they wish to specialize. (EQ2 Stratics) 
<br />

<br />
- The creation process will clearly inform players of all of the relevant race and class particulars. Players will actually see the progression paths their character can take throughout the course of the game. (HomeLan) 
<br />

<br />
- There will be more than one character slot per account per server. (EQSquare) 
<br />

<br />
- Religion and belief are very significant and play an important role for all characters, but especially for the priests and crusaders. (EQSquare) 
<br />

<br />
- Known Subclasses: Fighter, Priest, Mage, Scout, Artisan. The Fighter, Priest, Mage, and Scout archetypes are made up of three classes each. The Artisan archetype has two classes. Each class is made up of two sub-classes. (Moorgard) 
<br />

<br />
New - There will be "key" levels in the sense that you will be required to do quests at certain points before you can advance further. These quests can be related to citizenship in your home city, class-specific duties, or a variety of other things. (EQ Stratics) 
<br />

<br />
New - We will have forms of character advancement beyond just the standard level and skill progression, such as ways to obtain spells, abilities, and items other than just raising your level and killing monsters. (EQ Stratics) 
<br />

<br />
Skills, Combat and Magic 
<br />

<br />
- There will be No “Sense Heading”. Have to use compass. 
<br />

<br />
- “Trade Raids” will essentially be enormous civil engineering projects that require the efforts of several players in order to create large structures (such as Temples) that will then provide huge benefits to other players. Maintenance of these structures will be another crucial task for trade’s people. 
<br />

<br />
- Since EQ2 will be awarding XP for making items, there is a crafting system that mimics Combat. Separate bars on the crafting interface track the item making progress and your Characters “Concentration”. As long as your concentration bar outlasts your item making progress bar you will be successful in making the item. But events will occur during crafting to complicate matters, and you will have to execute “maneuvers” (Which are Essentially trade-based spells) to deal with them. Maneuvers are chosen before crafting and are lined up on the left side of the interface so that when you see an “Alert” like: “Overheating Metal,” you can click on “Cool Metal to salvage the crafting process. Of course, maneuvers cost you concentration. Should your concentration run out… You Fail! But you only lose raw components and money you put into it. Happily, rare components aren’t lost. 
<br />

<br />
- Weapons have the potential to do different damage to different Mobs. Such as a Blunt weapon will have a higher damage effect on a skeleton due to the vulnerability to getting crushed vs. just cut… what’s a cut going to do to a skeleton, he has no blood to spill. 
<br />

<br />
- The EQ magic system is largely unchanged except for the addition of “Concentration” as a new spell resource. While you’ll still need mana to fire off any spell, concentration represents your character’s ability to maintain spells and will be primarily used to maintain buffs. So a Shaman can cast a slew of protective spells on party members and never have them run out just as long as that shaman (other classes too) keeps the mental bandwidth to keep them running. Should you need to reclaim concentration to cast a different spell, you can “shut off” any currently maintained magic and immediately recoup the necessary brainpower. 
<br />

<br />
- Items will decay and only tradesman classes will be able to repair them. Decay rate will vary depending on the quality of the item (ie epic weapons will decay much slower than fine steel). They will wear when players die, and repairs will become necessary, but they won't simply degrade while sitting in your bank, or from regular use for instance. (E3, Moorgard) 
<br />

<br />
- You will be able to create macros for different weapon/armor/spell set ups so you can toggle to whatever the situation demands without rearanging your inventory. (Computer Gaming World, May 2003) 
<br />

<br />
- You will be able to dirrect a portion of your attacks at different body areas of a target. So if a target dosn't have any armor covering its arms attack its arms to do more damage because there vulnerable. (Computer Gaming World, May 2003) 
<br />

<br />
- Combat will be experienced while on a ship as well. More details are unavailable at this time. (EQ2 Stratics) 
<br />

<br />
- Item wear will mean the item will occasionally have to be repaired. The average item will likely last as long as you need it, and once you've handed it off, after a while, it will likely break and be removed from the game world during the next owner's ownership. This is to stabilize the economy and make sure the market is not "flooded" as it became in EQ1. (EQ2 Stratics) 
<br />

<br />
- PVP - EverQuest II, like EQLive, is primarily a PvE (player versus environment) oriented game. The intent is to support two types of PvP within EverQuest II. One is a structured and competitive form of PvP that does not allow the players to directly fight other players, and will be available as an optional form of gameplay on all servers. No, this is not a new form of the PvP Flag. It is currently nicknamed IPvP, which stands for Indirect Player versus Player. The second form of PvP is the traditional EQLive server rule sets. Other features, not directly considered PvP, that will be supported include: player duels, competitive arena-style party combat with other player parties, structured guild wars (with repercussions and rewards), and other forms of consensual player versus player combat/interaction. These other features will be developed in both initial development and later LIVE development. (EQ2 Stratics) 
<br />

<br />
- Combat will include quite a few action-oriented modifications that will increase the intensity and interaction of a fight. Classic rogue-based skills such as lock picking will require more player attention and skill. (HomeLan) 
<br />

<br />
- The gathering skills for tradeskill items are a whole sub-set of fun things to do in that all characters will have access to. Everyone will be able to gather. Common components will be available on merchants as well. (EQSquare) 
<br />

<br />
- Once the encounter begins, the group you are dealing with is locked to your player group. Once that happens, no one outside your group can do anything to affect your encounter, such as steal your kills or heal the party. If things are going poorly, you can always unlock the encounter, opening it up to outside help. Once you do so, other players can aid you, but the rewards for the encounter will drop off significantly. (Frictionless Insight) 
<br />

<br />
- Group leaders will decide from a variety of forms of distribution how loot will be handled. Group members will be able to see the choice the leader has made and decide whether or not they wish to stay with the group. (Frictionless Insight) 
<br />

<br />
- Regeneration of health will be greatly increased BETWEEN battles (after all engaged mobs have been killed) to reduce downtime. (IGN@ECTS) 
<br />

<br />
- As far as skills go, there are three different types of skills - techniques, knowledges and arts. Techniques are the skills that are used to determine success or failure in a given action. Then knowledges are where a lot of specialisation comes in, because they're the enablers in the game - so every item and every spell in the game has a related knowledge ranking. (Computer and Video Games) 
<br />

<br />
- There will be special combat maneuvers while on a mount (Stratics) 
<br />

<br />
NPCs 
<br />

<br />
- More than 160 Unique Monster Types -- Encounter and fight dozens and dozens of monsters 
<br />

<br />
- Mobs are Tougher and smarter than EQ1, they have a dramatically complex new pathing system that will prevent mobs from attacking through walls and other objects. 
<br />

<br />
- Mobs can follow you anywhere within a zone and they will be able to zone with you. They will eventually give up pursuit, so speed will be a major factor in outrunning mobs. 
<br />

<br />
- A direct answer to the grefing tactic of pulling large trains of Hostile Mobs into a cluster of underpowered players is that EQ2 mobs will stay focused on the player who pulled them. Once that player dies or Escapes, mobs that have moved out of their “Area of comfort” will ignore other potential targets and make a beeline for home, thus protecting innocent players. Of course, some Mobs at higher-level zones are going to feel at home (Area of Comfort) just about anywhere in that zone. 
<br />

<br />
- EverQuest II uses an encounter rather than creature-based system for combat. This means that while occasionally players will run into the simple single-creature encounter, more often than not there will be a number of other variables adding to the experience. On the simplest level this will mean that groups of players will interact with groups of NPCs. The resulting behaviors, tactics and circumstantial factors that add to that encounter, however, will make for a continuously changing variety of experience. (HomeLan) 
<br />

<br />
- Certain groups of monsters and NPCs work together, so rather than finding lots of lone gypsies wandering in a set area, you’ll find a camp of gypsies working together. You’ll be able to con (consider the strength of) a foe by moving the mouse pointer over them – the color and shape of the cursor will indicate the level of threat and reward. If a group works together, all the members of the group will be highlighted when you con one member (unless the designers have planned an ambush). (Frictionless Insight) 
<br />

<br />
- If you have started a quest for a particular NPC and pass by him without having completed it, they will pester you for updates, asking how you are getting on and so forth.(IGN@ECTS) 
<br />

<br />
XP, Quests and Raids 
<br />

<br />
- Instead of taking away XP with death, the game will levy an “XP Debt”. Its like a credit card: a certain % of all XP you gain post-mortem will go toward paying off your dept, so death will only put a temporary drag on your advancement. Or you can just log off- XP dept will expire slowly over time on its own, so you should be good to go 24 hours later offline. 
<br />

<br />
- The current death penalty system has two options upon character demise. You can: a) Sacrifice an appropriate item (more on this further down) and return to an appropriate bind point with all other items intact and equipped or b) remain in your corpse until another player or event resurrects you. The sacrifice choice is intended to be the lesser-used choice. The item chosen for sacrifice will be based on the player's level mainly, and IS intended to be something with value to the player. Obviously, certain types of items would be excluded from this mechanic. To use a comparison from EQ1 terms of value, like an epic quest item or raid-level boss loot would not be considered for this sacrifice in almost all cases. The resurrect choice is intended to be the common choice. Two important bits of information relating to this: the Priest archetype gains a form resurrection at a VERY early level and you stay with your corpse when you die. This means you will never see a situation where the character exists alive within the world and has a corpse within the world. You're one or the other, never both. They will be closely monitoring the sacrifice system to gauge the item loss value, and balance it so that the system reinforces "death IS a bad thing" but not an excruciating event. (EQ2 Stratics) 
<br />

<br />
- Tradesperson will get XP for successfully creating new Items, Items that will be AMONG the very best in the game. 
<br />

<br />
- Raids will be available to all level ranges (no more powergaming to high levels to be able to raid). 
<br />

<br />
- There will be instancing but it will be used sparsely. EQ2 will implement instancing to make sure that players don’t find themselves struggling for the same content over and over again. Instancing will also allow far more detailed scripted events to be carried out. (E3) 
<br />

<br />
- Quests will evolve the political and social climate of the game. (E3) 
<br />

<br />
- It will take approximately the same amount of time to reach level 100 as it took to reach level 50 in EQ1 (Allakhazam's) 
<br />

<br />
- In the style of EQOA, killing a mob with a group will reward each group member with almost the same amount of xp as if they had each killed it solo. (Allakhazam's) 
<br />

<br />
- No more hunting for the right trigger word with Quests. A dialogue box will appear that will guide you through the Quest Dialogue. (Allakhazam's) 
<br />

<br />
- A Quest Journal will keep you up to date on your quests. 
<br />

<br />
- Newbie Quests will be available much like EQOA, that guide you through a series of quests that both gains you respectable items, and teaches you about the game. However, these quests will not be mandatory, and can be skipped without worrying about losing out on an ability or spell. (Allakhazam's) 
<br />

<br />
- Past the Sub-Class decision point, which currently takes place at Level 30, the player will have several pools of discretionary points to spend to increase their skill caps. Actual skill points are still earned through use. (EQLounge) 
<br />

<br />
- Quests can be given time limits to introduce a sense of urgency. Rewards can be granted just for witnessing certain events, such as the previously mentioned eclipse. Players can even garner rewards for participating in mini-games such as foot races or fishing tournaments. (Frictionless Insight) 
<br />

<br />
- Your progress in quests will affect your reputation with the NPCs of Norrath. You’ll begin as a stranger to the population, but as you complete quests they’ll begin to call you by name. If you perform enough high-profile tasks they may gossip to one another about you. (Frictionless Insight) 
<br />

<br />
- As you progress through any given quest, the game will 'remember' your status, thus allowing you to achieve the end goal in one or two hour 'blocks' rather then one continuous session. Read: No more time sinks. (IGN@ECTS) 
<br />

<br />
- Epic-style quests will be included in the game. (Stratics Q&A 1) 
<br />

<br />
Player Buildings and Social Structure 
<br />

<br />
- Advanced Chat, Guild and Grouping System -- Faction belief systems, advanced chat and grouping options 
<br />

<br />
- Players will be able to communicate with their guild in both EQ and EQ2 (if the guild exists in both games). 
<br />

<br />
- Every player will have some sort of access to a secure player housing, either by renting a room in an Inn or pooling in resources to buy a guild Hall. Players will be able to purchase land and housing. The structure that a player builds on his land is upgradable. 
<br />

<br />
- Supporting the social scene, areas will be set aside for public performance (plays, tournaments, poetry readings, weddings, and so on). Tradespeople can even own limited-seating playhouses, then charge other players to come see a performance. A rating system lets you know what’s popular and what isn’t, and affects the rates charged for admission. 
<br />

<br />
- Player communication will be open and seamless across both games and all servers. 
<br />

<br />
- Setting is 500 Years after EQ1 
<br />

<br />
- "Once you are logged into either version of EQ, you'll be able to communicate with any player in either game, across all the servers." (Computer Gaming World, May 2003) 
<br />

<br />
- There will be a large focus on making the tradeskill classes an integral part of the Everquest world, where relationships will form by people being dependant upon tradeskills, and tradeskills being dependant upon the combat classes. This way, if you decide to pursue the non-confrontational path as a tradeskill class, you will not find yourself feeling useless or unwanted in Norrath, but instead provide integral services to players as you work on your own form of advancement. While not much was said about the tradeskill classes in specific, nor the tradeskills themselves, Bill assured us that it was far more entertaining then hitting a ‘combine button’ and was excited to describe the tradeskill system as “robust”. (E3) 
<br />

<br />
- There will be two types of housing - player housing and guild housing. While player housing will be open to everybody, and far more accessible, he explained that Guild Housing would indeed have limited availability. (E3) 
<br />

<br />
- Guild Houses will be less customizable than player houses, but will be mostly unique, designed by the EQ artists especially for that purpose. They are massive in size, and magnificent in design. (E3) 
<br />

<br />
- Banks WILL be universal, as they are in EQLive. (Moorgard) 
<br />

<br />
- There will be completely player-run events (ie Best of the Best tournaments) where players will be able to build the arenas, and make and sell the tickets. (E3) 
<br />

<br />
- You will have keys to your home and be able to give your friends keys to allow them access to your home. (Caster's Realm Video) 
<br />

<br />
- "As for repairs, the transaction will be a secure one, not involving, giving the item to the tradesman, and it will not have a failure rate, which releives a lot of frustration." (E3) 
<br />

<br />
- Inn housing will be available to all and will be "instanced." (Anyone remember The Realm?) Plot housing will be viewable externally from the game world and will be limited. (EQ2 Stratics) 
<br />

<br />
- EverQuest II utilizes a powerful dialogue tree system that will allow players to interact with NPCs in a variety of ways. Although the primary use of this system is to communicate with NPCs in the world, it will also expand quest delivery, world-object interaction and a few other surprising areas of game play. (HomeLan) 
<br />

<br />
- The currency system will be the same as EQLive. (EQLounge) 
<br />

<br />
- Guild Houses will be able to contain tradeskill devices and other objects. (EQLounge) 
<br />

<br />
- Guilds will be able to purchase large "apartment" type instanced halls for their guild hall. (Moorgard) 
<br />

<br />
- When you get drunk everything gets all blurry and moves in and out of focus. Not like it did in EQ; like it does when you're really, really wasted and the barstool suddenly feels like it's made of jello. (Moorgard) 
<br />

<br />
- Instead of the faction system of EQ1, EQ2 has a "belief" system. As you kill certain monsters (or complete quests, I'd imagine), your faction changes. Monsters will react on you based on faction. Related monsters might share beliefs, so the effects are more complex than a simple faction system. (ECTS) 
<br />

<br />
- Obtaining houses will be heavily based on "faction" with the city in which you wish to build. This faction will deplete over time, so it will be necessary to remain in good standing with the city. (IGN@ECTS) 
<br />

<br />
- Freeport and Qeynos are the only starting citys. Freeport is for evil characters and Qeynos for good characters. 
<br />

<br />
- The first tier of player housing will be quite affordable, even for newer players. (Q&A 1) 
<br />

<br />
- Languages will be a big part of the game. For instance, certain dungeons will have their own unique language that must be learned in order to unlock quests, spells and other content. One of the tradeskill classes will be focussed on discovering such knowledge. ()Game Club Interview) 
<br />

<br />
- There are 3 types of social structures: Guilds, Families, and Fellowships. (EQ Vault Q&A 2) 
<br />

<br />
- Guilds will be much like they are in EQLive except they will be registered within the city they were founded and must pledge allegiance to one of the five factions of the city. They will be in competition with other guilds for favored faction, and as they earn more, they will receive tangible benefits. (EQ Vault Q&A 2) 
<br />

<br />
- Families will be another sort of organization that will all share the same last name. They will not be in any sort of competition with eachother, as in guilds.(EQ Vault Q&A 2) 
<br />

<br />
- Fellowships will be a group of six people whom have pledged to help eachother. They will grow together and share a pool of experience. Experience will be distributed even when players are offline.(EQ Vault Q&A 2) 
<br />

<br />
- Players and guilds align themselves to specific factions within their home city, and their contributions determine how prominent each faction is within the world. If the Qeynos military faction is more prominent than the Freeport military, for example, all citizens of Qeynos will receive bonuses to their combat techniques. Members of the faction that is most dominant in the city will receive additional benefits. Likewise, the guild with the largest contribution to the most prominent faction will receive perks of their own, including special housing and access to lucrative tasks and valuable items. (EQVault) 
<br />

<br />
Boats and Travel 
<br />

<br />
- Porting will be available to a larger range of classes, but evacs will remain more specialized to druid and wizard type classes. (E3) 
<br />

<br />
- Due to the fact that the face of Norrath has been broken into numerous continent-sized islands, boats will play a key part both in the initial exploration of the world and in the ongoing adventures that will persist throughout the life of the game. At launch, players can expect to run into many classic high seas encounters. Pirates, sirens and monsters from the deep will all seek to destroy or waylay the player explorers. But the adventure that players will find on the deck of their ships is not limited to the expected . . nor to 'adventure' in the traditional sense. (EQ Vault) 
<br />

<br />
- Players can own boats which they will be able to fully control (pirate anyone?), and other modes of transport including mounts (though horses will not be included at innitial release).(E3) 
<br />

<br />
- Some islands will only be visitable after certain quests are completed. (ECTS) 
<br />

<br />
- During boat travel, you will be able to select destinations based on how much of the world has been rediscovered. Finding new islands will involve research and following clues. Once a new area has been found, other players will be able to select that place as a destination.(Q&A 1) 
<br />

<br />
- The ships we have at launch will be designed to carry a single party. There will of course be room on deck to deal with any unexpected visitors that may turn up en route to your destination. Larger ships might be an option in the future.(Q&A 1) 
<br />

<br />
Miscellaneous 
<br />

<br />
- In-game Journals -- players can log information regarding quests, adventures, encounters, transactions, etc. 
<br />

<br />
- EQ2 camping of Mobs should be limited due to the new “Pocket Zone”. This is similar to the “Anarchy Online” when you triggered a quest or met specific requirements, you are (and your group, if needed) taken to a zone that is essentially your own. Sony will be able to create as many pocket zones as necessary for any players at the same point at the same time- so no more waiting. 
<br />

<br />
- An All Access Pass will allow you to play EQ, EQ2, EQOA, Planetside and all Station Pass Games for $21.99/month. But still wont be able to import your EQ1 toon over to EQ2. Sony is working on an “Ancestral” plan, in which your new EQ2 character could be the descendent of one of your EQ1 characters. Your descendent will carry an “Heirloom” from your older character- maybe a piece of Jewelry or Armor. 
<br />

<br />
- Binding spots are scattered across the land. 
<br />

<br />
- You can create macros of different Armor/Weapons/Spell set-ups, so you can easily toggle to whatever the situation demands without laboriously rearranging everything in your inventory. 
<br />

<br />
- There will be exclusive crossover quest zones in each game that will be accessible only by subscribers of both games, allowing characters in EverQuest and EverQuest II to gain access to hidden treasures, an EverQuest II in-game reward for loyal fans. 
<br />

<br />
- Takes place in the massive world of Norrath, which revisits familiar locals as well as introduces a number of newly discovered areas (50% old and 50% new?) 
<br />

<br />
- It will be easy-to-use for beginners and gradually get more complex the higher level you are to smooth out the learning curve. (E3) 
<br />

<br />
- We should be seeing a beta this fall. (E3) 
<br />

<br />
- Final release scheduled for early 2004. 
<br />

<br />
- EQ2 Fighting animations were captured in a large part from Keanu Reeve's stunt double from the Matrix movies. (IGN) 
<br />

<br />
- Character animations were created by motion capture photography. 
<br />

<br />
- Inventories will be able to auto sort items to make efficent use of space. (Computer Gaming World, May 2003) 
<br />

<br />
- EQ2's ui is xml based as well- in fact currently about 1/3rd to 1/2 of the ui in eq2 is EQ's. as they get the "new" ui windows done they replace the old window in game. The goal is for an existing EverQuest player to feel very comfortable with the interface and basic play of the game while experiencing the newer mechanics and content introduced. Elements such as the weapon configuration menu and a customizable interface are important to our goal of ease of use, so that the player can focus on enjoying the game. (EQ2 Stratics) 
<br />

<br />
- The first time a player travels to any given location, they must physically traverse the wilderness (whether that be land or water-travel, or anything in-between). While traveling, they will encounter teleport spires which they can attune themselves to; and once attuned, be able to teleport to any spire they have visited from any other spire. There will also be other methods of long distance travel, but all of them tend to follow this view. This includes personal and group teleport-type spells. We are implementing these in such a way that non-spellcasting classes are not at a disadvantage. (EQ2 Stratics) 
<br />

<br />
- Players will immediately recognize the names of many of the locales in EverQuest II, but the face and character of these locations will differ greatly from previous incarnations. This mixture of the familiar and the unknown will inspire a sense of exploration rooted in the well-known. Nektulos Forest? Who knows what it looks like NOW. (HomeLan) 
<br />

<br />
- Moorgard has been assigned for Public Relations for Everquest 2. 
<br />

<br />
- The timeline will be based upon the months and seasons of Norrath. Norrath winter consists of a season called Decay and includes the months of Firstchill, Deadening, Deepice, and Grayeven. We will have different environments with snow and rain. And the seasons will affect the frequency of various weather phenomena. Freeport gets the occasional shower, but not snow. (EQSquare) 
<br />

<br />
- Daylight and sky will be interactive with the weather and the seasons. "The city of Qeynos has a few epic structures such as a monumental sword towering in a central plaza, and a grand, central castle. If you stand so that the top of the sword lines up with the highest point in the castle, twice a year you may be treated to an eclipse, just over the sword’s tip. There are even efforts to establish a harmony between magic and the sky. For example, the eclipse may be associated with grand magical effects, and powerful spells could conceivably light up sympathetic constellations in the sky." (Frictionless Insight) 
<br />

<br />
- There will be a variety of "death animations" (EQ2 OGaming) 
<br />

<br />
- Real-time translation in English, French, German, Japanese and Korean (ToTheGame)
<br />

<br />
